{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01SmkGNsqVA8kZvgK5uq1uJn","type":"tool_result","content":"14-1. **Access to private data** — The agent can read source code, credentials, API keys,\n15-   internal documentation, or customer data.\n16-2. **Exposure to untrusted content** — The agent processes inputs that an attacker could\n17:   influence: issue descriptions, pull request comments, dependency READMEs, web pages,\n18-   or fetched API responses.\n19-3. **Ability to communicate externally** — The agent can make HTTP requests, send emails,\n20-   push to remote repositories, or otherwise transmit data outside the local environment.\n--\n40-```\n41-workflow \"main\" {\n42-  step prepare-prompt {\n43:    run = \".cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n44-    results = [success, fail]\n45-  }\n46-\n--\n56-}\n57-```\n58-\n59:In this pattern, the host workflow uses a *script* step (deterministic, no LLM) to\n60-prepare the prompt and a *workflow* step to dispatch it to a container. No agent step\n61-runs on the host.\n62-\n--\n66-  permissions rather than your personal user account.\n67-- Avoid setting broad environment variables (cloud credentials, database URLs) in the\n68-  daemon's environment. Only export what is strictly needed.\n69:- Keep host workflows simple — use them for orchestration (scripts and workflow dispatch),\n70-  not for direct agent work.\n71-\n72-## Network Allowlisting\n--\n183-that reaches an agent's prompt can instruct it to take unintended actions.\n184-\n185-**Separate trusted and untrusted content.** Prompt templates in `.cloche/prompts/` are\n186:trusted — you write and review them. User requests (task descriptions, issue bodies) are\n187-untrusted — they come from external sources. Cloche's prompt assembly concatenates these,\n188-so the agent sees both. Keep the trusted template's instructions clear and explicit to\n189-reduce the chance of injection overriding them.\n190-\n191:**Validate external inputs in script steps.** Use host-side script steps to sanitize or\n192:filter task descriptions before passing them to agent steps. For example,\n193:`.cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh` can strip HTML, limit length, or reject suspicious\n194-patterns before writing to `$CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT`.\n195-\n196-**Limit feedback content.** The `feedback = \"true\"` step config includes previous output\n--\n217-\n218-| Risk | Mitigation |\n219-|------|-----------|\n220:| Host-side agent has full access | Use container workflows for agent steps; keep host workflows to scripts and dispatch |\n221-| Unrestricted network in container | Declare `network_allow`; enforce with Docker-level network controls until runtime enforcement lands |\n222-| Sensitive files in container | Rely on copy-based isolation; avoid bind mounts; audit overrides |\n223-| Credentials leaking | Pass via env vars at runtime, not in images or overrides |\n224:| Prompt injection | Sanitize untrusted inputs in script steps; keep prompt templates explicit |\n225-| Malicious agent output | Review branches before merging; check for unexpected changes |"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01Kj2ES3fjZGEh5kyGTHhvDA","session_id":"e576fc45-fcda-491a-aa5c-2d5791efc9e9","uuid":"cfa04a81-14ac-4892-b2f1-3c6509ba9780"}
